"'''Lumiya: Dark Star of the Empire'''" is a short story written by [[Michael Mikaelian]], featured in [[Star Wars Galaxy Magazine 3|''Star Wars Galaxy'' #3]] which was published by [[Topps|The Topps Company, Inc.]] in Spring [[1995]]. The story was also available online at [[Hyperspace: The Official Star Wars Fan Club|Hyperspace]]. It takes place in [[4 ABY/Legends|4 ABY]], sometime after the [[Battle of Saijo]]. Besides the main story, ''Dark Star'' also contains much of the title character's backstory, which can be found in [[Lumiya|her article]].

==Plot summary==
[[Lumiya]]'s [[EF76 Nebulon-B escort frigate/Legends|Nebulon-B frigate]] [[Revenant (EF76 Nebulon-B escort frigate)|''Revenant'']], escorted by the [[CR90 corvette/Legends|CR90 corvettes]] ''[[Wolf-Pack]]'' and [[Borealis (CR90 corvette)|''Borealis'']], flies through the [[Cron Drift/Legends|Cron Drift]] en route to Communications Research Station [[Epsilon Nine]] so as to obtain a progress report from the [[Galactic Empire/Legends|Imperial]] forces there, who have been conducting top-secret research. An [[Ensign/Legends|ensign]] then reports [[New Republic/Legends|New Republic]] [[Comlink/Legends|comlink]] frequencies coming from Epsilon Nine, indicating a Republic takeover of the station, just as ''Revenant'' is [[Assault on Epsilon Nine|ambushed]] by nine [[T-65 X-wing starfighter/Legends|X-wing fighters]]. Lumiya commands ''Wolf-Pack'' and ''Borealis'' to fire on Epsilon Nine's laser batteries, and sends out two [[Squadron/Legends|squadrons]] of [[TIE/IN interceptor/Legends|TIE interceptors]] and [[TIE/sa tactical bomber/Legends|TIE bombers]], the former to destroy the X-wings, and the latter to assist the Corvettes. The X-wings are soon defeated, and Lumiya's fleet continues bombarding Epsilon Nine.

''Borealis'' dispatches two [[HAVw A5 Juggernaut|A5 Juggernauts]] onto the station, which plow through fences and barricades and destroy the outer blast doors. Red-armored [[Stormtrooper/Legends|stormtroopers]] soon follow, as a [[Lambda-class T-4a shuttle/Legends|''Lambda''-class shuttle]] leaves the ''Revenant'' for Epsilon Nine. When Lumiya, aboard the shuttle, arrives at the station, a stormtrooper reports that all Republic forces have been [[Death/Legends|killed]], and all personnel accounted for. Lumiya walks up to the [[Scientist/Legends|scientists]] and reminds them that they are to develop new [[Spy/Legends|spy]][[Satellite/Legends|satellites]] for [[Imperial Intelligence/Legends|Imperial Intelligence]], and that she will "overlook consorting with the enemy just this once." With that, Lumiya and her crimson stormtroopers board their shuttles and leave Epsilon Nine.

==Continuity==
This very short story published as part of the roleplaying game section of ''[[Star Wars Galaxy Magazine]]'' was notable for bringing [[Lumiya]] back into "modern" continuity. Lumiya was developed as a post-[[Star Wars: Episode VI Return of the Jedi|''Return of the Jedi'']] villain for the [[Star Wars (1977)|Marvel Comics ''Star Wars'']] series ([[1984]]-[[1986|86]]), transforming a [[Rebel pilot/Legends|Rebel pilot]] and [[Galactic Empire/Legends|Imperial]] [[Agent/Legends|agent]], Shira Brie, into a [[Cyborg/Legends|cyborg]] warrior dubbed the "Dark Lady of the Sith." In the mid-1990s, much of the material established by Marvel Comics had fallen by the wayside of continuity, but this ''Galaxy'' story was meant as a way of giving readers the ability to inject Lumiya into their roleplaying games. It anticipated a return of the character, who more than decade later would figure prominently in the [[Star Wars: Legacy of the Force|''Legacy of the Force'']] series.<ref name="TERC" /> 

